<h1>From Pierre Penet</h1>
<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationRight">hambourg le 17. Mars 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Jai la satisfaction dannoncer  Votre Excellence, quayant t inform le 11 du courant de larrive de Monsieur Adams votre fils, en cette Ville de Hambourg, venant de Copenhaguen, je me suis prsent aussitt en son Htel pour avoir lhonneur de le saluer, lui offrir mes services &amp; lengager de faire une visite au Ministre de France. Le mme jour je lai prsent au Premier Bourguematre &amp; Prsident du Senat de la ditte Ville de qui il a t trsfavorablement acceuilli. Le jour suivant Jobtins lagrment de le conduire au Senat o on dsiroit le voir; il y fut galement acceuilli.</p>
<p>Je lui ai donn pour socit Mess<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs.</span> C. Voght &amp; C<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">ie.</span> une des plus puissantes Maison de Hambourg qui lui procurera pendant son sjour tous les amusemens possibles<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> Je me vois, avec peine, priv du plaisir de tenir compagnie plus longtems  Monsieur Votre fils, esprant faire voile incessamment pour lAmrique tant pour y <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0340">[340<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0340.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>rgler mes Comptes avec les Etats &amp; les Particuliers, que pour prouver linnocence de ma cause &amp; linjustice que jai supporte.</p>
<p>Persuad que la Nation Amricaine saura mieux apprcier ma conduite que ne lont fait mes compatriotes surtout les Neg<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">ts.</span> de Nantes, Ville o jai fait fleurer le Commerce par celui que jai introduit de la Nouvelle-Angleterre, &amp; o pour rcompense, jai support les plus affreux vnemens sans avoir pu jusqua ce moment obtenir aucune justice, pas mme rponse au mmoire que jai eu lhonneur de vous communiquer  la Hae.</p>
<p>Si vous avez des paquets  faire passer en Amrique, je men chargerai avec plaisir.</p>
<p>Jay lhonneur dtre avec le plus profond Respect, / De Votre Excellence, / Le trs-humble &amp; trs- / Obissant serviteur.</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">P: Penet<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="translation">
<h2><span class="hi-all-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase;">Translation</span></h2>
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationRight">Hamburg, 17 March 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I have the satisfaction to advise your excellency that, having been informed on the 11th of the arrival of your son, Mr. Adams, from Copenhagen, I immediately went to his hotel to have the honor of greeting him, offering my services, and urging him to visit the French minister. That same day I introduced him to the first burgomaster and president of the senate of our town, who accorded him a most favorable reception. The following day I had the pleasure of escorting him to the senate, where his presence was desired and he was similarly welcomed.</p>
<p>I introduced him to the firm of C. Voght &amp; Co., one of the most powerful houses in Hamburg, who will arrange all possible entertainments during his stay.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> With regret, I find myself unable to keep him company longer, as I hope to set sail forthwith to America. I intend both to settle my accounts with the states and particular individuals and to prove the innocence of my cause and the injustice I have suffered.</p>
<p>I am convinced that the American nation will better appreciate my conduct than did my countrymenespecially the merchants of Nantes, a city to which I introduced a flourishing New England trade, receiving in return the most appalling treatment and being unable until now to obtain any form of justice, not even a reply to the memoir I had the honor of sending you at The Hague.</p>
<p>If you have packets to send to America, I shall attend to them with pleasure.</p>
<p>I have the honor to be, with the most profound respect, your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">P: Penet<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-sn">
   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); endorsed by John Thaxter: M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> P. Penet / 17. March 1783.</p>
</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0341">[341<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0341.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0001">1</a>
   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr>s Diary and letters contain nothing about his activities in Hamburg, despite the fact that he remained there almost a month (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Diary of John Quincy Adams&lt;/i&gt;, ed. David Grayson Allen, Robert J. Taylor, and others, Cambridge, 1981. ]">JQA, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diary</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0002-0021%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0003-0001%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0004-0001%20ADMS-print-03-01-02-0005-0005-0001#ADMS-03-01-02-pb-0174" class="pageNo">1:174</a>). This makes Penets report concerning his efforts on behalf of <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Quincy Adams (17671848), son of John and Abigail Adams ]">JQA</abbr> of particular interest, but see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-14-02-0243" class="document">Lagaus letter of 4 April</a>, and note 1, below.</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0224-fn-0002">2</a>
   <p>Since 1775 Penet had involved himself in a series of unsuccessful ventures to provide the United States with military supplies, first in America and then at Nantes as part of the firm of Penet, da Costa Frres &amp; Company. Forced into bankruptcy in 1782, he fled his creditors and was preparing to return to America to settle his affairs. Penet wrote to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> from Germany on 20 Oct. 1782, flattering <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> with reports of Dutch and German esteem for him, asking <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> for his continued personal support, and offering <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> assistance in Germany while Penet awaited passage to America (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>). Penets letter to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> was not, however, a defense in the same sense as his letter of the same day to Benjamin Franklin (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Benjamin Franklin&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Leonard W. Labaree, William B. Willcox, Claude A. Lopez, Barbara B. Oberg, Ellen R. Cohn, and others, New Haven, 1959. ]">Franklin, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>, 38:234236), and no reply by <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> has been found. For detailed accounts of Penets activities, see <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Robert Morris, 17811784&lt;/i&gt;, ed. E. James Ferguson, John Catanzariti, Elizabeth M. Nuxoll, Mary A. Gallagher, and others, Pittsburgh, 19731999; 9 vols. ]">Morris, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>, 2:321; Thomas J. Schaeper, Pierre Penet: French Adventurer in the American Revolution, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Daughters of the American Revolution Magazine</span>, 117:854856 (Nov. 1983).</p>
</div>
